ğŸ§  What Are Annotations in Kubernetes?

ğŸ‘‰ Annotations are key-value pairs attached to Kubernetes objects (like Pods, Deployments, Services, etc.).
They are used to store non-identifying, metadata information â€” things that tools or automation systems might need, but that Kubernetes itself doesnâ€™t use for scheduling or selecting resources.

âš™ï¸ Syntax Example

Hereâ€™s a sample Pod manifest with annotations:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: demo-pod
  labels:
    app: myapp
  annotations:
    description: "This pod runs the demo application"
    createdBy: "Sumanth"
    checksum/config: "f4a9f1d7c8e1"
spec:
  containers:
    - name: demo-container
      image: nginx

ğŸ§© Annotations vs Labels
Feature	Labels	Annotations
Purpose	Used for grouping, selecting, and filtering objects	Used for attaching non-identifying metadata
Used by	Kubernetes core system (selectors, matchLabels)	Humans, tools, or controllers (e.g., Helm, ArgoCD, CI/CD pipelines)
Queryable (via selector)?	âœ… Yes (kubectl get pods -l app=myapp)	âŒ No
Example	app: nginx	description: "Managed by Helm"
ğŸ’¬ When to Use Annotations

Use annotations when you want to store:

Tool-specific info (e.g., Helm release name)

Version or checksum of configuration

Contact info for maintainers

URLs, docs, or change history

Debug or audit metadata

Sidecar injector data (used by Istio, Linkerd, etc.)

ğŸ§° Common Real-World Examples
ğŸ”¹ Helm
annotations:
  meta.helm.sh/release-name: "myapp"
  meta.helm.sh/release-namespace: "default"

ğŸ”¹ ArgoCD
annotations:
  argocd.argoproj.io/sync-wave: "1"

ğŸ”¹ Istio Sidecar Injection
annotations:
  sidecar.istio.io/inject: "true"

ğŸ”¹ Documentation Example
annotations:
  kubernetes.io/description: "Backend API service for user authentication"

ğŸ§  Key Points to Remember

âœ… Annotations = extra info for humans or tools

âŒ Not used by Kubernetes for grouping or selection

ğŸ“¦ Stored as metadata in the objectâ€™s metadata.annotations field

ğŸ’¾ No size limit per annotation, but total annotations per object should stay under 256 KB
